did.unittitle: Rockefeller Foundation records, projects, SG 1.16-1.19 (A90-A93)
did.langmaterial: Multiple languages contained in written material specific to country/region. Predominately written in English.

processinfo.head: Processing Information note
processinfo.p: Standard processing was conducted by Gail Antos. All records have been placed in acid free lignin free folders and rehoused in archival document storage boxes. Original order and original folder titles have been primarily maintained.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Project files transferred to the RAC by Rockefeller Foundation, 1990-1993.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.
RG 1.16 is arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure.

Subsequent subgroups are arranged by program, with RG 1.17 being the most prominent transition period where some materials are arrranged by the outgoing traditional series/subseries, and others are arranged by program.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Records more than 10 years old are open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. RAC is unable to provide access to obsolete media and original digital media. In addition separated media may not yet have undergone stabilization procedures. When feasible, a digital surrogate may be created via special order. All applicable charges will apply.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Rockefeller Foundation has title, copyright, and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them. Rockefeller Archive Center has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Types of records include: projects files and related material.

The arrangement of the material in RG 1.17 reflects this transition.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Record Group 1.18 is arranged by program. Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center recognizes that our audiovisual materials may contain problematic language and/or content.

The films, videos, and/or sound in this collection have not been altered in any way. All titles and/or content are illustrative of the creator's original vision. As such, this audiovisual collection may contain discriminatory visual and/or aural content that is representative of racial, gendered, or ableist biases.

Accompanying description, most often with creator or donor-generated language and terminology, has to this point been retained and maintained "as received" by RAC with minimal archivist intervention or augmentation.
We acknowledge these problems and aim to cultivate inclusive representation and equity by reconsidering and enhancing our description of this audiovisual material with current sensibilities.

Choreographers Meeting: Trisha Brown, Eliot Feld, Paul Taylor - Part 1

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Taped meeting at Rockefeller Foundation offices with choreographers Trisha Brown, Eliot Feld, and Paul Taylor. Brainstorming discussion about how to shape and develop a new RF choreographers program (Grant RF86006). Topics include: What should the grant criteria be?; Who should be funded?; What is the selection process?; Who should select?; Can a selector overcome personal bias?; Is selection subjective - or can it be objective?; How much should the funding amount be?; What is the grant trying to accomplish?; Where in the dance world is the need? Also, the choreographers discuss their methods of creation, as well as the difficulty of career continuity in dance. RF officers present (initials): ABA, HK, ESB, AAM.
